{"tier":4,"question":"What is perfect competition?","answer":"A market with many buyers and sellers, identical products, free entry/exit, and perfect information","choices":["A market where all firms make equal profits","A market with many buyers and sellers, identical products, free entry/exit, and perfect information","A market regulated to ensure equal outcomes","A market with no government involvement"]},
{"tier":4,"question":"What is the difference between microeconomic and macroeconomic equilibrium?","answer":"Micro equilibrium is where supply meets demand in one market; macro is where total output meets total spending","choices":["They are the same concept","Micro equilibrium is where supply meets demand in one market; macro is where total output meets total spending","Macro equilibrium only applies to international trade","Micro equilibrium requires government intervention"]},
{"tier":4,"question":"What is a liquidity trap?","answer":"When monetary policy becomes ineffective because interest rates are near zero and people hoard cash","choices":["When a bank runs out of cash reserves","When monetary policy becomes ineffective because interest rates are near zero and people hoard cash","When investors prefer bonds over stocks","When a country cannot borrow internationally"]},
{"tier":4,"question":"What is the output gap?","answer":"The difference between actual GDP and potential GDP","choices":["The gap between exports and imports","The difference between actual GDP and potential GDP","The growth rate needed to reduce unemployment","The difference between real and nominal GDP"]},
{"tier":4,"question":"What is economic rent?","answer":"Payment to a factor of production above what is needed to keep it in its current use","choices":["Income from renting property","Payment to a factor of production above what is needed to keep it in its current use","The return on capital investment","The cost of land in urban areas"]},
{"tier":4,"question":"What is the efficiency wage theory?","answer":"Firms pay above-market wages to increase worker productivity and reduce turnover","choices":["Higher wages always reduce unemployment","Firms pay above-market wages to increase worker productivity and reduce turnover","Wages naturally equal the marginal product of labor","Government intervention is needed to set fair wages"]},
{"tier":4,"question":"What is creative destruction?","answer":"The process by which new innovations replace old industries and methods","choices":["Government breaking up monopolies","The process by which new innovations replace old industries and methods","Inflation eroding the value of savings","Business cycles eliminating inefficient firms"]},
{"tier":4,"question":"What is the income effect in consumer theory?","answer":"When the price of a good falls, the consumer's real purchasing power increases, changing consumption","choices":["Higher income always increases demand for all goods","When the price of a good falls, the consumer's real purchasing power increases, changing consumption","Consumers always buy more when prices rise","Income tax changes consumer spending proportionally"]},
{"tier":4,"question":"What is the substitution effect?","answer":"When the price of a good falls, consumers substitute it for relatively more expensive alternatives","choices":["Consumers always prefer the cheapest option","When the price of a good falls, consumers substitute it for relatively more expensive alternatives","People substitute goods when their income falls","Businesses find cheaper production methods when wages rise"]},
{"tier":4,"question":"What is the difference between contraction and expansion in business cycle terms?","answer":"Expansion is a period of economic growth; contraction is a period of declining output","choices":["They are the same phase","Expansion is a period of economic growth; contraction is a period of declining output","Expansion increases inflation; contraction reduces it","Contraction only refers to a full recession"]},
{"tier":4,"question":"What is the trade-off between inflation and unemployment described by?","answer":"The Phillips Curve","choices":["The Laffer Curve","The Phillips Curve","The IS-LM model","The Beveridge Curve"]},
{"tier":4,"question":"What is the difference between short-run and long-run in economics?","answer":"In the short run, some inputs are fixed; in the long run, all inputs are variable","choices":["Short-run is less than one year; long-run is more than one year","In the short run, some inputs are fixed; in the long run, all inputs are variable","The long run always leads to equilibrium","Short-run analysis is always less accurate"]},
{"tier":4,"question":"What is price discrimination?","answer":"Charging different prices to different groups based on their willingness to pay","choices":["Illegal pricing of essential goods","Charging different prices to different groups based on their willingness to pay","Lowering prices to eliminate competition","Raising prices during peak demand"]},
{"tier":4,"question":"What is the debt-to-GDP ratio used to measure?","answer":"A country's debt sustainability, comparing what it owes to what it produces","choices":["The total income of a country","A country's debt sustainability, comparing what it owes to what it produces","The amount of money a country borrows each year","The difference between exports and debt payments"]},
{"tier":4,"question":"What is capital deepening?","answer":"Increasing the amount of capital per worker, raising productivity","choices":["A country investing in natural resources","Increasing the amount of capital per worker, raising productivity","The accumulation of financial reserves","Building more infrastructure in rural areas"]},
{"tier":4,"question":"What is the difference between gross and net investment?","answer":"Net investment equals gross investment minus depreciation","choices":["Gross investment includes imports; net investment does not","Net investment equals gross investment minus depreciation","Gross investment is by firms; net investment is by the government","They measure the same thing"]},
{"tier":4,"question":"What is utility in economics?","answer":"The satisfaction or benefit a consumer receives from consuming a good or service","choices":["The practical use of a product","The satisfaction or benefit a consumer receives from consuming a good or service","The total value of goods produced","The cost of an item relative to its price"]},
